<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · What we service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Commercial griddles are the workhorses of LA breakfast restaurants, diners, and high-volume kitchens.</h2>

    <p>Pancakes at 325°F, eggs at 350°F, burgers at 400°F, bacon at 425°F. Twelve to sixteen hour service days. Continuous heat cycling. Commercial griddles handle the breakfast and lunch volume LA restaurants depend on, and they break in patterns we recognize by brand and zone configuration.</p>

    <p>The brands we see daily: <strong>Vulcan VCRG-24, VCRG-36, VCRG-48</strong> (ITW Food Equipment Group, the dominant LA commercial mid-range). <strong>Garland Master Series ED-24, ED-36, ED-48 plus GD heavy-duty</strong> (Welbilt, premium tier). <strong>Star-Max 615, 824, 836</strong> (Star Manufacturing, Middleby brand, mid-range value). <strong>Keating Miraclean</strong> (independent, premium chrome-plated cooking surface). <strong>Wells G-13, G-19, G-24</strong> (independent, electric specialty). <strong>Bakers Pride XX series</strong> (Standex).</p>

    <p>Commercial griddles differ from residential cooking equipment in every way. Thermostatically-controlled cooking surface (precise 350 to 450°F control), heavy-gauge steel or chrome plate (3/4 to 1 inch thickness, residential is 1/4 inch), multiple zones with independent thermostats for left, center, and right regions, gas burners 25,000 to 30,000 BTU per zone. Different machine, different repair scope.</p>

    <p>Our techs service the full commercial griddle lineup across LA County, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. Gas griddles (most common), electric griddles (Wells specialty), chrome plate vs steel plate, single-zone vs multi-zone configurations.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair, no emergency surcharge. <strong>BHGS #A49573</strong> license. <strong>EPA 608 Universal #1346255700410</strong>. CSLB C-20 HVAC scope. BBB A+ accredited. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical griddle failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Eight failure modes account for nearly every commercial griddle service call.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Thermostat drift (year 4 to 7).</strong> Temperature control accuracy degrades, plate temp inconsistent across zone. Calibration $290 to $440, or replacement $440 to $720 per zone.</li>
      <li><strong>Igniter failure on gas griddles (year 5 to 8).</strong> Ignition wear from continuous high-heat cycling. Per-zone igniter replacement $260 to $440.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermocouple wear.</strong> Gas safety component, drops millivolt output below valve threshold, burner won't stay lit. $220 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Burner head clog (per zone).</strong> Grease and carbon buildup affecting flame distribution. Cleaning service $180 to $290 per burner.</li>
      <li><strong>Plate seasoning failure or surface degradation.</strong> Improper cleaning leads to plate damage. We don't resurface plates, but we coordinate with specialty plate resurfacing trade and document plate condition.</li>
      <li><strong>Drip tray drain blockage.</strong> Grease channel clogs, runoff backs up onto plate. Service $200 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating element burnout (electric griddles, Wells specialty).</strong> Year 7 to 10 typical. Per-element replacement $480 to $720.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-zone wiring or controller failure (electric).</strong> Control board $480 to $820. Diagnostic with zone isolation testing first.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 CONFIGURATIONS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Configurations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Gas vs electric, single-zone vs multi-zone, steel vs chrome.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Gas Griddles (Most Common LA Commercial)</h3>
    <p>Vulcan VCRG, Garland ED Master Series, Star-Max series. 24 to 72 inch cooking surface widths. Thermostatic control per zone. Multi-zone units have 2 or 3 independent thermostats. Steel plate (most common) or chrome plate (Keating Miraclean premium). Gas burners 25,000 to 30,000 BTU per zone.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Electric Griddles (Wells Specialty)</h3>
    <p>Wells G-13, G-19, G-24 series. Electric heating zones, more precise temperature control than gas, no gas line requirement, often used in lower-volume or specialty applications. Wells is the dominant brand in this category. Fewer LA shops handle electric griddles, we do.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Chrome Plate Griddles (Premium)</h3>
    <p>Keating Miraclean, plus some Vulcan VCRG-XX-1 chrome variants. Chrome plate cooking surface is easier to clean, no plate seasoning required, premium pricing $5,000 to $12,000+ vs steel plate $2,500 to $6,000. Year 12 to 15+ service life when properly maintained.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Multi-Zone Griddles</h3>
    <p>Larger units (36 inch+ widths) typically have 2 to 3 independent thermostatic zones. Independent zone temperature control allows simultaneous breakfast (eggs at 325°F) plus burger (350°F) plus bacon (400°F) cooking. Zone thermostat failures are a common service item, and the diagnostic is more complex than single-zone units. Most appliance shops misdiagnose multi-zone drift as a single-zone issue.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real repair stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Glendale · Vulcan VCRG-36 multi-zone gas, 6 years old</h3>
      <p>Diner. Left zone reading 25°F low, right zone igniter failing. Tested all three zones with calibrated probe. Calibrated left zone thermostat back to spec, replaced right-zone igniter. Total: $120 plus $290 calibration plus $290 part plus 1 hour = $560.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · Garland ED-48 Master Series, 8 years old</h3>
      <p>Breakfast restaurant. Annual major service: 2 thermostats out of calibration past acceptable drift, 2 igniters degraded, drip tray drain backed up with grease. Replaced both thermostats, both igniters, cleared drain. Total: $120 plus $880 parts plus 2.5 hours = $1,200. Owner does this annually as preventive maintenance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · Star-Max 824 chrome plate, 5 years old</h3>
      <p>Hotel breakfast buffet. Burner not staying lit on right zone. Diagnosed: thermocouple weak (8 mV, needs 18+ mV). Replaced thermocouple plus right-zone igniter while there. Total: $120 plus $260 parts plus 45 minutes = $440.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Wells G-24 electric griddle, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Specialty café. Right zone heating element burned out, year 9 typical for Wells G-series. Replaced element, tested zone temperature recovery. Total: $120 plus $580 part plus 1 hour = $720.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Long Beach · Vulcan VCRG-48 multi-zone gas, 7 years old</h3>
      <p>Burger chain location. Cascading service: 1 zone thermostat out of spec, 2 zones with igniter wear, 3 zone burner heads grease-fouled, drip tray drain blocked. All on one visit. Total: $120 plus $980 parts and labor across components = $1,400. Owner did the math against $4,200 replacement, repair was the call.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Burbank · Keating Miraclean 36 inch chrome griddle, 11 years old</h3>
      <p>Catering kitchen. Igniter wear plus thermocouple replacement. Chrome plate condition still excellent at year 11 (typical for Miraclean with proper cleaning protocol). Replaced both ignition components, verified chrome surface. Total: $120 plus $260 parts plus 45 minutes = $440.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

